 on the commercial covering. And the masonry in the bathroom is a little sloppy. Caulking spilling out of crevaces near the fawcett, wall paint on the door frame, etc...but you tend to notice these details more when other things are not working for you, right? In all fairness, the room itself was clean, the bed was made but, unfortunately, the bath towels did look a bit worn. To add insult to injury regarding the room, I put a bag on the coffee table in the room and the base slid off the pedestal that it was on, causing the glass to almost slide off as well. This is obviously not a quality establishment. The manager was pretty argumentative with me when she should not have been because we had never spoken and she heard my complaint through hotwire, not from me directly. Unless you are really, really, really on a tight budget i.e. student budget or are not looking for anything nice as far as hotels, amenities, etc...avoid the Hyde Park Suites. The &quot;suite&quot; is probably about the same size of a regular hotel room with 1 double bed. But it looks smaller because of the kitchenette. And the bathroom is very small. But even this can slide because it is London and rooms can run quite small. However, there is no air conditioning so I definitely don't recommend during the summer. In an effort to write a somewhat balance review, I will say that the kitchenette w/ modern finishes in the room is a good feature. The desk clerks were relatively helpful. Another good point is the location. The area is safe, vibrant and clean. It's close to paddington station and lots more attractions. But there are quite a few other hotels to choose from on the same street. I don't know what their rooms look like but the lobbies look like real lobbies, not a frat house and - I did ask around - the rooms have safes and phones. Sadly, the location only makes you wish you were actually staying somewhere nice rather than Hyde Park Suites. I could not even recommend this place if I were placed under hypnosis.	
